---

The maintenance corridor smelled like recycled nothing. Old air, old seals, the particular flavor of atmosphere that had been sitting in sealed ductwork for years and had forgotten what lungs were for. Autumn's boots found the deck plating by the sound it made — hollow, resonant, the kind of floor that told you there was nothing underneath except vacuum and prayer.

The cable spool weighed more than it should have. Military-grade shielding added mass the way paranoia added steps — everywhere, excessive, and entirely justified when you considered what happened without it. He'd rigged a carry strap from a cargo net he'd found in the bay, slung it across one shoulder, and was dragging the spool behind him like a man walking a very heavy, very uncooperative dog.

The corridor was dark except for the emergency strips along the baseboards — faded chemical luminescence, the kind that slowly dies over decades and was currently managing a dull amber that made everything look like it was rusting. His shadow stretched and compressed as he passed each strip. The generator assembly was on a makeshift dolly he'd cobbled from a maintenance cart, rolling behind him at the end of a tow line, its wheels protesting every seam in the deck plating with a sound like small mechanical complaints.

Twenty meters. In a well-lit corridor with a working gravity system and a cart that wasn't trying to murder him, twenty meters was nothing. In the dark, in partial gravity, dragging sixty kilos of cabling and a generator through a dead genetics colony, twenty meters was enough time to think.

He didn't want to think.

Thinking meant the cockpit. The cockpit meant her mouth against his, soft and deliberate and completely unsurprising in the way that the most important things are — you saw them coming for months and they still took you apart. Thinking meant Athrun Zala's face when she'd said what she said, and the five-day clock that was already four hours shorter than it had been when they'd docked, and the fact that the single most politically important person in the PLANTs was currently sitting in a dead archive with a bouncing pink ball for company because Autumn Ray existed and she'd decided that was enough reason to commit treason.

The corridor curved. Ahead, at the junction where the maintenance access met the archive wing, something pink glowed faintly.

He followed it.

The archive opened around him — high ceiling lost in darkness, rows of dead terminals stretching back into nothing, and there, at the far wall, Lacus Clyne.

Haro's lamp painted her in soft pink. She had a maintenance panel open, wiring exposed, a schematic projected on the wall behind her that she was cross-referencing with the junction in front of her. Her hair was tied back — not her usual style, something practical she'd done with a cable tie or a piece of wire, he couldn't tell from here. Her dress was still white, still impractical, still exactly what she'd wear to rewire a relay terminal in an abandoned space station because Lacus Clyne did not adjust herself to circumstances. Circumstances adjusted to her, or they didn't, and either way she'd be wearing the dress.

She turned at the sound of the cart wheels.

The look she gave him wasn't surprise. It was calibration — checking his state the way she always did, reading his fatigue and his mood and whatever else she pulled out of the space between his expression and his posture. Two seconds, maybe three. Then the small smile.

"You've brought everything?"

Her voice carried the same way it always did. Quiet, unhurried, slightly melodic. Like the dead colony was just another room and the five-day clock was just another schedule.

The cable spool hit the floor with a sound like a period at the end of a sentence.

